    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-10-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-10-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="545"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d545">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.50/2875</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Embassy</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Aide-Mémoire</hi>
                </p>
                <p>His Majesty’s Embassy enclose the text of a draft declaration<note n="47"
                        xml:id="d545fn47">See Conference Document No. 31, <ref target="#pg_736">p.
                            736</ref>, which is identical with the enclosure to this <hi
                            rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> except for the insertion of the word
                        “that” after “provided” in numbered paragraph 2.</note> which His Majesty’s
                    Government wish to propose under Items 3 and 11 of the British agenda for the
                    Three-Power Meeting.<note n="48" xml:id="d545fn48">See enclosure 1 to letter of
                        September 18 from the British Minister to President Roosevelt, <ref
                            target="#pg_525">p. 525</ref>.</note> Mr. Eden proposes to suggest that
                    this declaration should be discussed with a view to publication if agreed upon
                    at the meeting.</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-10-05">October 5,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[An <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> from the British Embassy in
                        Washington, October 5, 1943, enclosing a British note to the Soviet Chargé
                        d’Affaires in London on the subject of the negotiation by either the United
                        Kingdom or the Soviet Union of commitments or agreements with other European
                        governments in respect to questions covering the peace settlement or the
                        postwar period, is printed as Conference Document No. 23, <ref
                            target="#pg_724">page 724</ref>.</p>
                    <p>In a memorandum dated October 8, 1943, attached to the file copy of the
                        British <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>, the Chief of the Division of
                        European Affairs (Matthews) noted that on October 6 the Secretary of State
                        had consulted President Roosevelt with regard to the <hi rend="italic"
                            >aide-mémoire;</hi> Mr. Matthews’ memorandum continues, “The President
                        said that he did not think much of the proposed British draft. He further
                        said that it smacked too much [of] ‘spheres of influence’ policies, the very
                        thing which it was supposedly designed to prevent. Mr. Dunn informed Sir
                        Ronald Campbell that the President’s first reaction was unfavorable.”
                        (741.61/10–543)]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
